Lichens are symbiotic organisms between fungi and algae. Nearly 1100 bioactive metabolites have been isolated from 18,500 lichens, but still numerous organisms are yet to be discovered from different environments. These metabolites generally belong to the classes of polyketides, phenols, terpenoids or quinines. Several research studies indicated the antiviral activities of metabolites (
 Table 8 ), such as (+)-usnic acid, sekikaic acid, and anthraquinones against arenaviruses, respiratory syncytial virus, and HSV type 1 (
 Boustie and Grube, 2005; 
 Stocker-Wörgötter, 2008; 
 Zambare and Christopher, 2012; 
 Lai et al., 2013).
